\title{operantlunar: Differentiating Reward Maximization from Melioration via Operant Conditioning}
\description{
A tabular reinforcement-learning instrument that mechanistically differentiates reward-maximizing control (the law of effect) from descriptive melioration (the matching law). Provides a shared learning skeleton; a library of learning rules (Q-learning, SARSA, expected SARSA, double Q-learning, actor-critic, a model-based planner, gradient-bandit and rate-tracking melioration, win-stay-lose-shift); a battery of operant paradigms (schedule family, melioration trap, extinction, probability matching, self-control / delay discounting, differential reinforcement of low rates, progressive ratio, risk sensitivity, reinforcer devaluation, changeover-delay concurrent schedules); an analysis layer with generalized-matching, Herrnstein-hyperbola and discounting fits and a differentiation-matrix capstone; hashed tile coding with linear function-approximation agents and a generic Gymnasium adapter; an optional Python LunarLander environment via reticulate; and a bundled Shiny app.
}
